17.body: Weierstrass form y2=x3+ax+b Montgomery form by2=x3+ax2+x Edwards form x2+y2=1+dx2y2 Twisted Edwards form ax2+y2=1+dx2y2 Example 1 Simple example of an elliptic curve over a finite field F7​, i.e. the field of integers modulo 7. This means the field consists of elements {0,1,2,3,4,5,6}. Define an elliptic curve over F7​: y2≡7​x3+2x+1 The set of points (x,y) that satisfies this equation (along with a special point of infinity) forms the elliptic curve over F7​. To get this set of points, we need to cycle through values of x∈F7​ to get the corresponding y. For example, when x=1, we have: y2y2​≡7​13+2×1+1≡7​4​​ What are the values of y∈F7​ that satisfy this congruence? Let's enumerate them: When y=0, 02≡0≡7​4 When y=1, 12≡1≡7​4 When y=2, 22≡4≡7​4 When y=3, 32≡9≡7​4 When y=4, 42≡16≡7​4 When y=5, 52≡25≡7​4 When y=6, 62≡36≡7​4 Therefore, when x=1, y=2,5.

27.body: g is a primitive root modulo n, i.e. gk≡n​a for every a coprime to n. This means that the powers of g generate all numbers that are coprime with n in the modulo n sense. In other words, g is a generator (hence "g") for the multiplicative group of integers modulo n. 💡 Related to Fermat’s Little Theorem. Example 1: Primitive root prime modulo 3 is the primitive root modulo 7. 3k≡7​a Cycling through the values of k: 31≡7​332≡7​233≡7​634≡7​435≡7​536≡7​1 5 is also the primitive root modulo 7. 5k≡7​a Cycling through the values of k: 51≡7​552≡7​453≡7​654≡7​255≡7​356≡7​1 Note Primitive roots modulo n is used in Diffie-Hellman key exchange (iirc).

Corollary 2 For a prime modulus p and any integer k, ak≡p​akmod(p−1) Proof For a prime p, we can write k as a function of p k=r+q(p−1) where 0≤r<(p−1), which is the same as rmod(p−1). So ak​≡p​ar+q(p−1)≡p​ar⋅aq(p−1)≡p​ar≡p​akmod(p−1)​​

44.body: The Chinese remainder theorem states that for a system of congruences x≡n1​​a1​x≡n2​​a2​x≡n3​​a3​... if ni​ are pairwise coprime , then there exists a solution x≡N​s where N=∏i​ni​. Example 1 For a system of congruences xxx​≡5​2≡7​3≡11​10​​ where the moduli are pairwise coprime, a n | N n m y m n a*m*y x ≡ 2 mod 5 | 385/5=77 3 ≡ inv 77 mod 5 462 x ≡ 3 mod 7 | 385/7=55 6 ≡ inv 55 mod 7 990 x ≡ 10 mod 11 | 385/11=35 6 ≡ inv 35 mod 11 2100 -------------------------------------------------------- N=385 sum,s=3552 then x≡385​3552≡385​87 If we take 87+385=472 to be a possible solution, then we can verify that 472472472​≡5​2≡7​3≡11​10​​ How to realise the benefits of CRT? If we could break down N into, say, its prime factorisation, then we can simplify problems (by means of say faster computation) from x≡N​c to x≡p1​​cx≡p2​​cx≡p3​​c and calculate x≡N​s instead. Application of CRT: RSA In the decryption process of RSA, to find the original message m in m≡n​cd where c is the ciphertext and d the private key, knowing that n=pq, we instead solve for m based on the system of congruences m≡p​cdm≡q​cd which has a solution since p and q are pairwise coprime (because they are prime). We can simplify this system of congruences using Euler's theorem. Because p and q are prime, then m≡p​cd≡p​cdmod(p−1)m≡q​cd≡q​cdmod(q−1) Working: a n n m y a*m*y x ≡ c^d mod p | N/p=q inv q mod p g x ≡ c^d mod q | N/q=p inv p mod q h -------------------------------------------------- N=pq sum,s=g+h then m≡N​(g+h) This makes the computation faster in several ways: a — Reducing cd to moduli p and q (instead of n) m — This number can be computed once y — This number can be computed once

8.body: A group G is a set of elements that follows the following rules: Binary operation Closure ✅ Associativity ✅ Identity ✅ Invertibility ✅ Commutativity The number of elements of the group, ∣G∣, is known as the order of the group . Example of a group An example of a group is an analog clock. Groups may have: generators — a group can have either several or no generators. subgroups Given a group G and a subgroup H, the cofactor or index of the subgroup is the ratio ∣H∣∣G∣​ Groups can be: finite or infinite cyclic — if a group has generator(s) Elements of a group can: repeat have an element order
8.title: Groups

9.body: A "multiplicative" group is a group whose arithmetic operations between elements involve multiplications (one or many). Example 1 The set of real numbers, R. Example 2 The multiplicative group of integers modulo m is denoted by Zm×​. Counter-example 1 The set of integers, Z, does not form a multiplicative group. This is because the inverse of the elements are not integers. Question Why must a number be coprime to the group's modulus in order for it to have an inverse? Euler's totient function φ(n) is related to the order of the multiplicative group modulo p, where p is a prime number.
